Text: Looking back from my last post I'd say I was too optimistic about what I personally and what my team could achieve.
The Friday presentation demo should already give a hint into a lack of even the most basic CRUD functionalities in our app.
Even when our client has given us a list of what they think are top priorities, I still have a sense that they are a bit too much given that we only have 2 weeks left or real development.
It may come as a surprise since we as a team are quite technically capable, at least based on our track records.
However, I think picking up a new and relatively not beginner-friendly framework has started to bite at us.

Coming from the web development world where I can just attach an event handler to whatever I want with a minimal amount of code and even conceptual planning, I admit there were times last week where I wondered if it was all worth it when our chosen framework (Model - View -View Model) takes so much set up and boilerplate to essentially do the same thing.
And then I realize that the divide between the object-oriented world of C# and the event-driven realm of JavaScript is real.

It seems web apps are much more fleeting as compared to enterprise software, and that may explain why there's a lack of stress on SOLID as well as the absence of key concepts such as interfaces in the JavaScript world.
That said, I also noticed enough similarities to make good progress over the weekend, so I'm keen to show my team what I've managed to do and there will be some functionalities after all.
There's always an initial learning curve, so the fact that we've had a rather unproductive week speaks to something else about our team dynamics.
I joined the team late and all the technical decisions were already decided, even before our first client meeting.
While I don't really have any problem with that, and I'm grateful that they agree to take me on, I really think we could've made a better choice had we really sat down and be a bit more critical.
Still, I distinctly remember Gogo saying that the project is, to him, as much for us as for the client.

We don't know enough to really have a say anyway, so I guess it ultimately is about how each of us perceives our journey so far, rather than the end product, which probably will be a prototype at this rate.
So, in the end, I do think I've had a productive week, even if it's just adapting to how events are handled in the C# world.
Moreover, I think this experience would help if I ever decide to pick up similar front-end tech such as Google's Angular, which are also based on data binding like WPF.
Team-wise, my teammates are trying really hard and I appreciate that we are all sharing the struggle together.
It's funny how much joy we derived from putting a few lines inside a data grid.
But then that's the fun of programming, putting little pieces together and appreciating the little things.
For this week, my goal is probably the same as the rest of my team's.
We will try to finish all the basic functionalities while not letting MVVM gets on our nerves.
Overall
